export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "opener", "html": "<p>A 60 meV error in a lithium migration barrier is a factor-of-ten error in predicted diffusivity at 298 K. Across 574 DFT-NEB battery-chemistry migration paths, the five most-used foundation machine-learned interatomic potentials (MLIPs) miss those barriers by 0.310–0.349 eV on average — four to six times the reference method's own ~60 meV floor.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"2\">[2]</sup> That coupling — the largest quantified barrier error in this paper, astride the largest industrial bet — is why batteries anchor flagship discovery chain 1: the electrification stack is rate-limited by barrier errors.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s7-1", "html": "<p>Three 2026 facts frame the stakes. First, sodium-ion is commercial reality: CATL's Naxtra cells (175 Wh/kg, company-reported) enter GWh-scale mass production by end-2026, and the Changan Nevo A06 is the first mass-produced Na-ion passenger EV.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"204\">[204]</sup> Natron Energy, the US pioneer, folded in September 2025; at ~<span class=\"math\">$10k/t lithium carbonate, Na-ion still costs more than LFP.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"204\">[204]</sup> Second, solid-state has its strongest industrial commitments yet: Idemitsu took final investment decision on a sulfide-electrolyte pilot plant (January 29, 2026) plus a 1,000 t/yr Li$</span>_2<span class=\"math\">$S plant — electrolyte for 50,000–60,000 EVs — feeding Toyota's 2027–28 vehicles, full mass production admittedly after 2030.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"205\">[205]</sup> QuantumScape opened its Eagle Line pilot plant (February 4, 2026) and signed Honda (June 2026) — pre-revenue still, guiding a $</span>250–275M 2026 adjusted-EBITDA loss.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"206\">[206]</sup> Third, both governments pay for demand: DOE's third battery-supply-chain NOFO offers $500M (selections pending as of 2026-07-17),<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"54\">[54]</sup> and China's new-type storage fleet hit 136 GW/351 GWh at end-2025 under an official &gt;180 GW-by-2027 target.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"53\">[53]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"207\">[207]</sup> All three bets run on ionic transport and interfacial stability — the two quantities the simulation stack gets most wrong.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s7-2-1", "html": "<p>Bheemaguli, Xiao, and Sai Gautam compared five foundation MLIPs — MACE-MP-0, ORB-v3, SevenNet, CHGNet, M3GNet — against 574 curated DFT nudged-elastic-band (NEB) migration paths.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"2\">[2]</sup> Barrier mean absolute errors (MAEs) run from 0.310 eV (MACE-MP-0) to 0.349 eV (M3GNet); excluding 17 common outliers, 0.239–0.290 eV.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup> Diffusivity being Arrhenius in the barrier, a 0.3 eV MAE can misestimate room-temperature diffusivity by <span class=\"math\">$\\sim 10^5$</span>.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup> A community pre-review reproduces the MAEs within 8 meV (MACE-MP-0 lowest in 97% of bootstrap resamples) but notes three non-climbing NEB images can under-resolve saddles by 40–160 meV — the size of the inter-model spread.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"208\">[208]</sup> The caveat disciplines but does not reverse the conclusion: the friendliest numbers still sit ≥3× the DFT floor.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"208\">[208]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s7-2-2", "html": "<p>Worse than their size is their direction: CHGNet and M3GNet <em>underestimate</em> 73.1% and 78.2% of barriers (420 and 449 of 574 paths) — they systematically over-predict ionic conductivity.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup> Inside a screening funnel that is the worst bias imaginable: false-positive &quot;superionic&quot; candidates reach experimental queues. The failure concentrates at high barriers: in the 1.31–2.50 eV band, only 3.7% (CHGNet) to 20.7% (ORB-v3) of predictions land within 0.1 eV — borderline candidates are silently misranked.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup> Universals still earn their keep as classifiers — ORB-v3/SevenNet sort good-versus-bad conductors (500 meV threshold) at ~85%/~83% accuracy — and as NEB accelerators (&gt;66% better starts): accelerators, not oracles.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s7-2-3", "html": "<p>Barriers are not the only corrupted label. Raw GGA underestimates cathode voltages ~20% — 0.7–1 V for a 3.5–4 V olivine — through self-interaction error on transition-metal <span class=\"math\">$d$</span> states.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"75\">[75]</sup> DFT+U and hybrid functionals restore ~0.1 V agreement,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"76\">[76]</sup> but universal MLIPs trained on GGA-level corpora inherit the uncorrected bias (scoreboard Row 10). Crystal-graph ML voltage regressors add their own error: 0.24–0.33 V MAE in-domain, ~0.37 V and systematically low out-of-domain — against the ~0.05–0.1 V resolution that coatings and window rankings need.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"77\">[77]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s7-2-4", "html": "<p>The mechanism is settled: Deng et al. showed M3GNet, CHGNet, and MACE-MP-0 systematically soften the potential-energy surface (PES) at high-energy configurations, saddle points included, because pretraining corpora over-sample near-equilibrium structures; the error being a smooth, systematic slope error, one additional DFT structure per chemical system largely removes it.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"21\">[21]</sup> The bright spot is MatterSim: in Du et al.'s twelve-model solid-state-electrolyte (SSE) benchmark it scores best on nearly all metrics and matches DFT and experiment on Li<span class=\"math\">$^+$</span> diffusion coefficients, especially at room temperature.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"34\">[34]</sup> Its plausible advantage is actively sampled, wide-coverage training data (89 elements, 0–5000 K, ≤1000 GPa) — the non-equilibrium diet scoreboard Row 1 prescribes. That reading is my inference; documented caveats: a closed training set and a mid-pack Matbench Discovery stability rank — best for SSE diffusivity is not best everywhere.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"209\">[209]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s7-2-5", "html": "<p>The class hurts most where universals are worst. Dendrite penetration is a rare-event, chemo-mechanical, system-level phenomenon: lithium plates into pre-existing flaws, crack pressure reaches ~1 GPa in seconds, and the critical current density (CCD) is a processing property — LLZO cells short at 0.1 mA/cm² with contaminated interfaces, sustain &gt;1 mA/cm² dense and clean, and reach 6.5 mA/cm² under 1 MHz pulsed current — against industry targets above 5.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"210\">[210]</sup> The canonical simple theory already failed: Monroe–Newman predicted a separator with twice lithium's shear modulus (4.5 GPa) would resist dendrites; most solid electrolytes grow them despite moduli many times lithium's.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"210\">[210]</sup> A single-property funnel cannot see this failure mode, ps–ns MLIP-MD cannot reach it, and its governing high-energy states — crack-tip fields, under-coordinated lithium — are exactly what PES softening corrupts.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"21\">[21]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"210\">[210]</sup></p>\n<p><strong>Table 7.1 — The battery error ledger: barriers and voltages (verified as of 2026-07-17).</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Error quantity</th>\n<th>Value</th>\n<th>Basis</th>\n<th>Source</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Barrier MAE, full 574-path set</td>\n<td>0.310 eV (MACE-MP-0); 0.336 (ORB-v3); 0.343 (CHGNet); 0.344 (SevenNet); 0.349 eV (M3GNet)</td>\n<td>Foundation-MLIP NEB vs GGA DFT-NEB</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"2\">[2]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Barrier MAE, 17 common outliers removed</td>\n<td>0.239 / 0.245 / 0.275 / 0.251 / 0.290 eV (MACE / ORB-v3 / CHGNet / SevenNet / M3GNet)</td>\n<td>As above, 557 paths</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Barriers underestimated (false-positive bias)</td>\n<td>73.1% (CHGNet); 78.2% (M3GNet)</td>\n<td>Sign of signed error, all 574 paths</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>High-barrier accuracy (1.31–2.50 eV band)</td>\n<td>3.7% (CHGNet) to 20.7% (ORB-v3) within 0.1 eV</td>\n<td>Subset of paths</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>DFT-NEB reference floor</td>\n<td>~0.060 eV; 60 meV = 10× diffusivity error at 298 K</td>\n<td>Conventional DFT-NEB vs higher fidelity</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Cathode voltage, raw GGA</td>\n<td>~20% low (≈0.7–1 V for olivines); misses Li<span class=\"math\">$_x$</span>FePO<span class=\"math\">$_4$</span> phase separation</td>\n<td>Self-interaction error vs experiment</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"75\">[75]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Cathode voltage, DFT+U / hybrid</td>\n<td>~0.1 V agreement</td>\n<td>Derived-<span class=\"math\">$U$</span> and HSE vs experiment</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"76\">[76]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Cathode voltage, ML regressors</td>\n<td>0.24–0.33 V MAE in-domain; ~0.37 V out-of-domain (systematically low)</td>\n<td>Crystal-graph regressors</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"77\">[77]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>The ledger says three things. Barrier rows: no universal MLIP can rank electrolytes by conductivity — the best full-set MAE is five times the reference floor; the outlier-removed numbers, four. The underestimate row says the error is not symmetric noise but, for two models, a one-directional optimism that manufactures false positives no funnel averaging can wash out. The voltage rows say the inherited functional floor compounds the learned error: 0.7–1 V of raw-GGA bias sits underneath regressors that add 0.24–0.37 V of their own, when 0.05–0.1 V decides window rankings. The floor row is my standard: 60 meV is what DFT-NEB itself achieves; worse is a downgrade, not an approximation. Figure 7.1 puts the spread against that line.</p>\n<figure class=\"fig\"><img src=\"/charts/battery-barriers.png\" alt=\"Figure 7.1 — Barrier MAE of five foundation MLIPs vs 574 DFT-NEB paths, full set and outlier-removed, against the ~60 meV DFT-NEB floor (dashed).\" loading=\"lazy\"/><figcaption>Figure 7.1 — Barrier MAE of five foundation MLIPs vs 574 DFT-NEB paths, full set and outlier-removed, against the ~60 meV DFT-NEB floor (dashed).</figcaption></figure>\n<p><em>Source: Bheemaguli, Xiao &amp; Sai Gautam, arXiv:2512.03642 / Digital Discovery (RSC, 2026), d5dd00534e <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"2\">[2]</sup> — 574 curated DFT-NEB paths; outlier-removed series excludes 17 common outliers; floor per the same study. Data as of 2026-07-17.</em></p>\n<p><strong>Box 7.1 — Three electrolyte controversies, and what each costs a screening program.</strong></p>\n<p><em>(1) LGPS's diffusion dimensionality.</em> Li<span class=\"math\">$_{10}$</span>GeP<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>S<span class=\"math\">$_{12}$</span> (12 mS/cm, Kamaya 2011) was assigned one-dimensional <span class=\"math\">$c$</span>-axis channels; neutron/bond-valence work (2016) found &quot;quasi-isotropic three-dimensional&quot; pathways; ML-potential MD (2021) found mild anisotropy — <span class=\"math\">$c/ab$</span> diffusivity ratio ~3, in-plane two-dimensional paths rate-limiting — reproducing <span class=\"math\">$\\sigma$</span> = 12 mS/cm, <span class=\"math\">$E_a$</span> = 226 meV at 300 K.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"211\">[211]</sup> The flagship superionic conductor's mechanism was mis-assigned for years: small barrier errors flip the predicted rate-limiting channel.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"211\">[211]</sup></p>\n<p><em>(2) Li<span class=\"math\">$_6$</span>PS<span class=\"math\">$_5$</span>Cl's stability window.</em> The argyrodite's thermodynamic window is narrow: reduction below ~1.7 V vs Li<span class=\"math\">$^+$</span>/Li (to Li<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>P + Li<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>S + LiCl), oxidation above ~2.5 V — stable only across roughly 1.7–2.5 V.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"212\">[212]</sup> Measured windows look wider via kinetic intermediates: naïve hull windows understate practical stability, naïve CV readings overstate thermodynamic stability.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"212\">[212]</sup> Vendor datasheets nonetheless market &quot;&gt;7 V&quot; stability — nearly three times the upper edge of the thermodynamic window (7 V vs 2.5 V), propagating straight into cell-design failures.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"212\">[212]</sup></p>\n<p><em>(3) Halides versus lithium metal.</em> Chlorides such as Li<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>YCl<span class=\"math\">$_6$</span> (DFT window 0.62–4.02 V) and Li<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>InCl<span class=\"math\">$_6$</span> (2.38–4.26 V) are oxidation-stable to ~4.2–4.3 V, enabling uncoated 4 V cathodes (94.8% first-cycle coulombic efficiency with LiCoO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>; interfacial resistance 16.8 <span class=\"math\">$\\Omega$</span> cm² against a sulfide's 128.4), but are thermodynamically unstable against Li metal — growing interphases force hybrid sulfide-separator/halide-catholyte architectures.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"213\">[213]</sup> Here computation led experiment and was right; the open problem is interphase <em>kinetics</em> — a growing mixed-conducting interphase (MCI) rather than a passivating one — where long-time MLIP-MD is now being attempted.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"213\">[213]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"214\">[214]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s7-3", "html": "<p>The fixes are the scoreboard's two H-rated data levers. Row 1 — non-equilibrium pretraining: training identical architectures on rattled, strained, hot configurations instead of near-equilibrium trajectories cut out-of-distribution cleavage errors 5× (eSEN) and 17× (EquiformerV2); MatterSim's actively sampled corpus embodies the same idea and is the one universal matching DFT and experiment on Li<span class=\"math\">$^+$</span> diffusivity.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"19\">[19]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"34\">[34]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"209\">[209]</sup> Row 2 — systematic-error surgery: one DFT structure per chemistry removes most of the softening, and ~100 frames reach DFT-level accuracy (measured dose-response).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"21\">[21]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"87\">[87]</sup> The pragmatic 2026 stack is universal-for-relaxation, specialist-for-numbers: MLIP pre-relaxation accelerates NEB convergence in &gt;66% of cases,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup> and purpose-trained moment-tensor potentials reproduce AIMD ionic conductivity of LGPS-family SSEs to 3.1 mS/cm MAE (Pearson <span class=\"math\">$r$</span> = 0.965) at 1.5–3.9 meV/atom energy error.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"214\">[214]</sup> No group has demonstrated the solved target: barrier MAE ≤ 40 meV (≈1 kcal/mol) across chemistries. With Rows 1–2 that is within reach of demonstration — the unlock flagship chain 1 requires.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s7-4", "html": "<p>The §7.1 texture deserves a discount rate. Solid-state was ~0.1% of batteries sold in 2025 (~$1.6B); one market synthesis projects ~4% penetration by 2030, ~10% by 2035.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"52\">[52]</sup> Hyundai–Kia pushed its target to ~2030; Toyota leaves full mass production &quot;2030 or later&quot;; BYD and CATL say the same at earliest.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"215\">[215]</sup> QuantumScape weathered a 2021 short-seller report likening it to Theranos and the resulting class action; as of April 2026, ratings skew seven Holds, two Sells, no Buys.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"215\">[215]</sup> The skeptic case is slippage, test conditions, and yield — not cell physics; the counter-counter is 2025–26's B1 shipments, the Eagle Line, Honda validation, and the Idemitsu FID.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"215\">[215]</sup> My planning basis is the ~0.1%-to-~4% decade, anything faster treated as upside.</p>\n<p>The credibility discipline applies here first, because A-Lab's headline claims were battery materials. Berkeley's autonomous laboratory reported 41 novel compounds from 58 targets in 17 days (Nature 2023); Leeman, Schoop, and Palgrave found errors in its automated Rietveld refinement, mishandled compositional disorder, and absent confirmatory diffraction — &quot;no new materials have been discovered in that work&quot; (PRX Energy 2024); Nature's January 2026 correction walked back the novelty claims, not the robotics.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"29\">[29]</sup> Cheetham and Seshadri found &quot;scant evidence&quot; that GNoME's ~380,000 structures clear a novelty–credibility–utility bar; one review noted its Li-ion conductor examples carry soft-anion chemistries with narrow stability windows — Box 7.1's exact failure mode.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"216\">[216]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"217\">[217]</sup> Chapter 20 carries the full account; the lesson here: characterization error compounds computational error — a barrier-ridden funnel feeding an autonomous lab manufactures confident nonsense at scale.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s7-5", "html": "<p>Washington's instrument is midstream: DOE's NOFO DE-FOA-0003585 offers up to <span class=\"math\">$500M under IIJA §40207 for battery materials processing, manufacturing, and recycling at ≥50% cost share; applications closed in April 2026.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"54\">[54]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"218\">[218]</sup> Discovery-side accuracy sits with the Energy Storage Grand Challenge (\"50-by-30\") and the Long-Duration Storage Shot (90% cost cut to $</span>0.05/kWh; pack −44% to $80/kWh by 2030), neither backed by a public scorecard.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"219\">[219]</sup></p>\n<p>Beijing's instrument is deployment scale: the NEA puts new-type (non-pumped-hydro) storage at 136 GW/351 GWh at end-2025, +84% year-on-year.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"53\">[53]</sup> The NDRC/NEA action plan targets &gt;180 GW by 2027 with ~RMB 250bn direct investment,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"207\">[207]</sup> and CNESA's White Paper 2026 projects 371.2–450.7 GW by 2030 under the 15th Five-Year Plan.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"220\">[220]</sup> Utilization roughly doubled (611 h in 2023, 911 h in 2024) after mandatory co-location gave way to market-driven dispatch, rewarding the cheapest chemistry — LFP now, Na-ion next — while planning documents call solid-state a &quot;forward-looking reserve.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"221\">[221]</sup> Both governments, in short, pay for the demand side of the discovery chain; neither funds the barrier-accuracy problem it is gated on. That asymmetry is the opening.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s7-6", "html": "<p>Chain 1: barrier-accurate MLIPs → solid electrolytes and cathode coatings with verified ionic transport → 500 Wh/kg-class solid-state batteries → EV cost, grid storage, energy access. The quantified gap: 0.310–0.349 eV full-set MAE against a 60 meV floor; the solved target: ≤40 meV (≈1 kcal/mol), where MLIP-NEB becomes oracle rather than accelerator.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"2\">[2]</sup> My closing judgment is the one the numbers force: the 73–78% underestimate asymmetry is worse than the MAE itself. Symmetric error degrades every candidate equally and averages out across a large screen; one-directional underestimate optimistically biases every downstream funnel, in every chemistry, every time — it tells you the worst candidates are good. Hence my protocol: validate barriers and diffusivities against experiment before trusting any energy leaderboard — chain 1's first deliverable is a barrier-verified electrolyte screen, not a bigger candidate list. The class rate-limited by barrier errors is also where the cheapest demonstrated fixes apply; the burden of proof now sits with anyone screening superionic conductors on uncorrected universal potentials.</p>\n" },
]
